Boys and girls this is a textbook case of what not to do when you're in the service industry. When there are things that have sold out on the menu: warn people. If you fail to do that, apologize and say that it no longer is. There is no need for an attitude. I didn't purposefully go looking for things so you'll actually have to get up from your perch 10 feet away, come over and let me know that something is not sold. Or just don't sell it if it's gonna cause a serious problem......  I also don't believe its a good idea to yell at people when they didn't tip your suggested amount especially causing a scene in the middle of a street. This is just poor form. If you don't like it and if I were to happen to return (I wouldn't have anyway) then reduce the service. That said scenes were started, mistakes, were made and here we are with this review announcing the waitstaff here have severe attitude problems.  Pro Tip? There's a perfectly good Shanghainese restaurant right next door. The red cooked pork is fire and the xiao long bao are not half bad. No attitude, no questions asked, they get my full middle of the road 20% tip.

A staple in the Chinatown community. I've been coming here for 15+ years and will continue to support the mom and pop restaurants. The food is great for the price and you'll be able to get simple all day dim sum here! I highly recommend coming here!! (the original Hong Kong style cafe in Chinatown).

Super affordable, simple, Hong Kong teahouse food. Everything’s just as slapdash as a no-frills cafe, with the toast being literally just toast, and the tea the perfect amount of milky and bitter. I particularly enjoyed the turnip cake, which was pan-fried until crispy brown, a great improvement over most dim sum places’ soggy steaming.
Simple, cosy, very inexpensive, and delicious - just perfect - order set D breakfast to stay warm on a cold wintery morning

This place is incredibly cheap! Incredibly. I came here with my friend and both of us were surprised at the low prices. I ordered a Beef Fried Rice thinking it was for one person. It was for two. For the price of $8 for two people is amazing.  They also have a HUGE variety of foods, so I'm sure anyone can find anything.  The only thing I'd complain about is the atmosphere/service. Perhaps the values are different but it's not like your traditional food place. You have to make your presence known to the servers  Other than that, it's definitely a 4/5

This place use to be my go to place for weekend breakfast, now not so much. It does get busy sometimes but the wait is usually no more than 15 mins. It was much better couple of years ago  but I feel like the food and the drink hasn't age well. The coffee and the HK milk tea is plain, the food sometimes is hit or miss especially the spicy beef ramen noodle which I get a lot. If there a line, I would skip the place but if this is your first time, or you just want a quick bite, give it a try.
Good place with authentic Chinese food from Hong Kong.

Love hate relationship with this place. This is the real deal if you are asking for old school, nostalgic old Chinatown with mean street food. First like someone reviewed if you go with this bogie attitude you will dislike the place. The service is not friendly, hasty and very Chinese in America. Real deal! I love the screaming in Cantonese in the kitchen because that is what makes it old Chinatown, not catering to the tourists and American Chinese generations like me. No organic, just fresh made to order meals. NO frills but truly HK...the decor might frighten some. Now the food, I like their congee, fish ball curry and rice noodles minus PB though. Have yet tried noodle dishes. Big on take out clients but I recommend eating rice noodles there. Places like this is hard to come by..nowadays.

Authentic, old school feel. The food is actually really tasty. I love their toast, it is the best butter toast I have anywhere else. Must order is the satay beef instant noodle, the satay beef is amazing, I used to have it everyday for like half a year until I got really sick of it. The ham and egg macaroni taste very authentic. The congee and rice noodle combo is a must. The breakfast combo comes with a drink. Honestly, for a cheap meal $6, it is very affordable.
My go to spot for HK style milk tea. Aso their breakfast options are good too, getting my quick fix of HK cha chang tang without going all the way to HK.

Hong Kong style cafe. Humongous menu. Many choices even in style of noodles for the noodle soups. 13 people in group and tried many items. Best was Hong Kong milk tea. Had iced because it was a 100 degree day. Noodles with different dressings was good. Oven cooked Pork chop rice was good. Beef tendons was hard as a rock. Wonton noodles was very good. French toast is good. They have ham and beef sandwiches also. Too many to list.

This was my first stop in NYC, We arrived on a bus around the corner from here around 10 AM and came here for breakfast. One IMPORTANT tidbit that you should have before you go: You must flag down your waitress to take your order, if you do not do this, you will not be served. I don't know why, this wasn't something I ran into anywhere else in NYC but right before I got mad and walked out an Asian lady sitting beside us told me this and as soon as I tried it, the service and food was very fast! My husband and I both got the ham omelets with fries, toast and a drink and our total was only $10.15! The food was great and a great value! If you are riding a bus into Chinatown this could be the perfect place for you to stop for food before going into town!

Honestly the best place I found to eat some classic breakfast in Chinatown. They have the classic dim sum, the classic letter breakfast specials A,B,C,D,E. Food gets here quick. Neighborhood service. Pros: 1. Small and cozy place. It's got a small family feel to it. Typically I go once or twice a month at most and have had long stretches of not going. But the staff there remember me and be quite hospitable. 2. Great food. It's essentially a Hong Kong version of, not fast food, but quick service, highly comforting food. There's an array of breakfast items, steamed rice rolls, noodles, drinks, rice dishes, etc. The portions are reflective of most Chinese dining establishments. 3. Reasonable pricing. In all the time I've been their customer, about 7 years, I dont think their prices have risen. The breakfast deals are definitely a must try for the value of it as well as the "homey" feel.  Cons: 1. This is half a con - there is usually a 15 minute wait during peak hours. That makes sense since the place is so good! Just be cautious that if you're starving, dont expect a table right away during peak hours.  Personal input: I absolutely love their French toast. Note that it is NOTHING like the American version. This is light and fluffy on the inside and deep fried, then topped with a slab of softened butter and maple syrup.

M-Star Cafe serves typical Hong Kong style fares. The ambience isn't the greatest, but it's cleaner than most of Chinatown's legacy establishments.  Everything's pretty good and reasonably priced. Some of my favorites include HK steamed rice rolls, congee, macaroni in soup, and pork chop over rice with curry sauce. Make sure to get the half coffee / half tea iced drink. It's done correctly.

Sunday brunch.  Place is packed but wait was pretty quick at 10:45am.  Service is fast and efficient.  The waiter and waitresses have pretty good memory.  When my party ordered, the waitress didn't write one thing down! After taking our orders, I was very worried that she would mess something up, and watching her go to another table to take another order made me worry even more.  When the food came to my table, everything we ordered and added extra was made to perfection and executed like a hit man.  Damn this waitress had good memory, I only wished my memory was as good as her.  Ordered from the breakfast special (morning -11am) combo A toast and spam omelet.  You can get a cup of coffee with the combo, or add $1 for ice coffee/milk tea, and ordered a side dish of HK style steams rice noodles (soy and peanut sauce). Friends ordered Combo D- Ramen and toast, and french toast.  Even if the place is packed, the food came quick.  Food tasted really great.  It definitely tasted like authentic Hong Kong style brunch and high tea time meals.  Decor of the place reminded me of some authentic spots in Hong Kong.  Called M Star cafe, they were trying to copy an actual restaurant in Hong Kong owned by movie stars.  Not sure if this has any connection, but their decor is painted with popular HK pop and movie stars.  I can see that they started their wall of celebrities who have came to visit.  I can only hope more movie stars come to visit this solid spot.

True HK fusion and most people from Hong Kong agree that this is as authentic as it gets in Manhattan. Forget about the tea houses. Order that plate and look at the portion, look at the sauce being poured, this is HK Fusion in New York.  Though they don't have every possible item you can order from Hong Kong, it certainly is more than sufficient. The interior design is also very special and lively with some of the most famous actors and singers as comic drawings.

I'm not entirely sure why it says "burgers" for the description on yelp.  This place has a nice authentic feel and I imagined myself in Hong Kong.  Something is definitely still missing though.  Probably the hustle and bustle outside.  Or.. the PEANUT BUTTER in my french toast. -_- haha I guess here you have to specifically order it with the peanut butter?  It was still really filling though.  The milk tea is definitely not the best.. like some other yelpers say.  The best milk tea is definitely STILL in hong kong itself.  NO ONE CAN COMPARE!  The place is not that huge and they didn't have the a/c on while I was there on a hot summer day.

This is a place is how I would imagine a typical Hong Kong cafe to look like as depicted in some of the Chinese series I've seen, so I really love the whole feel of the place. They have green plastic chairs that are surprisingly comfortable and the service was decent. This place doesn't get too busy, so you get your order generally pretty quick. I really like their accent wall where it depicts a bunch of HK celebrities in caricatures and it's fun trying to identify everyone. The food was pretty good and tasty. I would definitely go back to check out some of their other dishes because I didn't get everything I want from the menu.

Walk toward Division St. in Chinatown and you will find this blue-tiled restaurant, very unique since it stands out from the rest of the other restaurants that are there. M Star Café is a Hong Kong based café that serves some of the common western breakfasts, like ham and macaroni, but with a slight Asian twist. Why “M Star” you may ask…well, because when you walk in, you will see caricatures of Hong Kong movie stars and artists (musicians) on their wall. The life-like characters (at least the head part) are not only recognizable by many Chinese people, but these characters are drawn with elongated bodies that make them look oddly weird, but entertaining. I usually frequent this place for breakfast, but they also serve lunch and dinner. My recommendation would be the Portuguese baked chicken over rice dish, since I feel like this dish has a better representation of east meets west fusion. Prices are reasonable since it’s under $10. They make some of the finest milk teas, especially when tea is not watered down, so the milk tea is pretty caffeinated to get your day going. Service, however, lacks a little since the waiters are always on the rush, so they tend to forget a lot. They can completely forget your order, or misplaced your order, but in general, they still serve some good tasting meals.
